<subSubSection id="1CA06543FFF4FFE6D7BA8B87FE56FE0B" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF4FFE6D7BA8B87FF74FEBF" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D7BA8B87FECDFF6B" bold="true" box="[189,328,158,184]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Etymology:</emphasis>
—The specific epithet is a tribute to the German explorer, geographer and naturalist Friedrich Wilhelm Heinrich Alexander von Humboldt (1769–1859), who was originally honoured by the name Hansa Humboldt, the original name of Corupá, the Brazilian municipality where the new species, according to the best of evidence, is restricted to. The village of Hansa Humboldt was founded by German immigrants in 1897, and had its original name forcibly changed to Corupá in 1944 as part of Getúlio Vargas’ policy of persecution of the German-speaking population in 
<collectingCountry id="2CAD7658FFF4FFE6D7A28A4BFF68FEBF" box="[165,237,338,364]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF4FFE6D7BA8A6FFE56FE0B" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D7BA8A6FFEC6FE43" bold="true" box="[189,323,374,400]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Phenology:</emphasis>
—Confirmed flowering and fruiting: January. This species was seen alive during the late autumn and winter, but not fertile. Thus, it is probably that species blooms along the summer and parts of spring and autumn, as most of the Brazilian species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CA06543FFF4FFE1D78F8AF8FE9CFDF3" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF4FFE6D78F8AF8FECEFD97" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D78F8AF8FEA1FE28" bold="true" box="[136,292,481,507]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Distribution:</emphasis>
—The new species is only known from the 
<typeStatus id="8B01886AFFF4FFE6D4348AFBFCE6FE2F" box="[819,867,482,508]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">type</typeStatus>
locality, in Salto Grande waterfall, in the Emílio Fiorentino Battistella Natural Heritage Particular Reserve, in Corupá municipality, northern 
<collectingRegion id="967EF82AFFF4FFE6D390891FFABAFDF3" box="[1175,1343,518,544]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Santa Catarina</collectingRegion>
, southern 
<collectingCountry id="2CAD7658FFF4FFE6D78F8933FF49FD97" box="[136,204,554,580]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="CC812A4DFFF4FFE6D7DC8933FEBBFD97" box="[219,318,554,580]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[136,229,1538,1560]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,605,1513]" captionTargetId="figure-187@3.[151,1436,605,1513]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution map of Persicaria humboldtiana." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5753701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5753701/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Figure 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="00C56640FFF4FFE6D78F8D1BFD38F9C4" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5753701" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5753701" box="[136,701,1538,1560]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5753701/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" startId="3.[136,229,1538,1560]" targetBox="[151,1436,605,1513]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF4FFE6D78F8D1BFD38F9C4" blockId="3.[136,701,1538,1560]" box="[136,701,1538,1560]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D78F8D1BFF7BF9C4" bold="true" box="[136,254,1538,1560]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
Distribution map of 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF4FFE6D6C08D1BFD32F9C4" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[455,695,1538,1559]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D6C08D1BFD32F9C4" box="[455,695,1538,1559]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF4FFE6D7BA8D5FFDF1F923" blockId="3.[136,1452,1606,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D7BA8D5FFEA6F9B3" bold="true" box="[189,291,1606,1632]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Habitat:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF4FFE6D6398D5EFDDDF9B3" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[318,600,1606,1632]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D6398D5EFDDDF9B3" box="[318,600,1606,1632]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits humid rocks along the riverbanks, at permanently humid spots due to constant splashing, and is susceptible (and seemingly resistant) to occasional flooding. The new species occurs in the same locality and environment as the narrowly endemics 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF4FFE6D4688D97FB76F97A" authority="Hassemer" authorityName="Hassemer" authorityYear="2016" box="[879,1267,1678,1705]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Plantago" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D4688D97FBF9F97B" box="[879,1148,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Plantago humboldtiana</emphasis>
Hassemer
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D3F98D96FA91F97B" box="[1278,1300,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF4FFE6D21A8D96FEEAF91F" author="Hassemer, G. &amp; Ronsted, N. A. H." pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="2050" refId="ref4782" refString="Hassemer, G. &amp; Ronsted, N. A. H. (2016) Yet another new species from one of the best-studied neotropical areas: Plantago humboldtiana (Plantaginaceae), an extremely narrow endemic new species from a waterfall in southern Brazil. PeerJ 4: e 2050. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.7717 / peerj. 2050" type="journal article" year="2016">Hassemer &amp; Rønsted (2016: 4–9)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF4FFE6D6A18DABFC62F91F" authority="Funez et al. (2020: 80 - 87)" authorityName="Funez" authorityPageNumber="80 - 87" authorityYear="2020" box="[422,999,1714,1741]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Ludwigia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D6A18DABFD36F91F" box="[422,691,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Ludwigia humboldtiana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF4FFE6D5BE8DAAFC62F91F" author="Funez, L. A. &amp; Farias, D. M. &amp; Hassemer, G. &amp; de Gasper, A. L." box="[697,999,1714,1741]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="77 - 89" refId="ref4521" refString="Funez, L. A., Farias, D. M., Hassemer, G. &amp; de Gasper, A. L. (2020) Ludwigia humboldtiana (Onagraceae), a narrowly endemic new species from the subtropical Atlantic Forest, southern Brazil. Phytotaxa 470: 77 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 470.1.3" type="journal article" year="2020">
Funez 
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D4028DAAFCBBF91F" box="[773,830,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
(2020: 80–87)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, what demonstrates the high importance of this habitat for biodiversity conservation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF4FFE6D7BA8DE3FCB2F83F" blockId="3.[136,1452,1606,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D7BA8DE3FE30F8C7" bold="true" box="[189,437,1786,1812]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Conservation status:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF4FFE6D6D68DE2FD6EF8C7" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[465,747,1786,1812]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D6D68DE2FD6EF8C7" box="[465,747,1786,1812]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here assessed as Critically endangered CR according to the criterion B2a,b(iii) of IUCN (2019). The area of occupancy (AOO) of less than 
<quantity id="93429B2DFFF4FFE6D3358C07FBF4F8E8" box="[1074,1137,1822,1851]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" unit="km" value="2.0">2 km</quantity>
², with only one population known. This population is located within an environmentally protected area (Emílio Fiorentino Battistella Natural Heritage Particular Reserve); nevertheless, the species unfortunately cannot be considered satisfactorily safe, because of the ongoing trend of reduction of environment protection areas in the region, due to the pressure caused by the agricultural advance in 
<collectingRegion id="967EF82AFFF4FFE6D6888CB7FDE9F81A" box="[399,620,1966,1993]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Santa Catarina state</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF4FFE6D57C8CB7FCEFF81A" author="Hassemer, G. &amp; Ferreira, P. M. A. &amp; Trevisan, R." box="[635,874,1966,1993]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="78 - 95" refId="ref4710" refString="Hassemer, G., Ferreira, P. M. A. &amp; Trevisan, R. (2015) A review of vascular plant endemisms in Santa Catarina, southern Brazil, highlights critical knowledge gaps and urgent need of conservation efforts. Journal of the Torrey Botanical Society 142: 78 - 95. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.3159 / torrey-d- 14 - 00033.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Hassemer 
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF4FFE6D5F58CB6FCAFF81B" box="[754,810,1966,1992]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
) and in 
<collectingCountry id="2CAD7658FFF4FFE6D4C38CB7FB8DF81B" box="[964,1032,1966,1992]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Brazil</collectingCountry>
as a whole, leading to the conversion of natural environments in agricultural and silvicutural lands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF3FFE1D7BA8B87FBB5FEBF" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,545]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D7BA8B87FE8CFF6B" bold="true" box="[189,265,158,184]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Notes:</emphasis>
—This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D5878B86FCC4FF6B" authorityName="Opiz, Seznam Rostlin Kveteny Ceske" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Huds." box="[640,833,159,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D5878B86FCC4FF6B" box="[640,833,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Persicaria minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a cosmopolitan species common in Eurasia and North America, with only one record in South America, in 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D5D58BDBFB87FF0F" authority="(Cialdella 1989)" baseAuthorityName="Cialdella" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[722,1026,194,220]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Fanerogamica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="argentina">
Argentina (
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF3FFE1D4578BDBFC7FFF0F" author="Cialdella, A. M." box="[848,1018,194,220]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="179 - 246" refId="ref4071" refString="Cialdella, A. M. (1989) Revision de las especies argentinas de Polygonum s. l. (Polygonaceae). Darwiniana 29: 179 - 246." type="journal article" year="1989">Cialdella 1989</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Despite the similarities due the small size of the vegetative and reproductive characters of both species, 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D4978BFEFBCEFED3" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[912,1099,230,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D4978BFEFBCEFED3" box="[912,1099,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily differentiated due its petiolate, broadly lanceolate leaves (
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D5188A12FDB8FEF7" box="[543,573,267,292]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">vs.</emphasis>
sessile, linear lanceolate leaves in 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D4B88A12FB98FEF7" authorityName="Opiz, Seznam Rostlin Kveteny Ceske" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Huds." box="[959,1053,267,292]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D4B88A12FB98FEF7" box="[959,1053,267,292]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Another very useful characteristic to distinguish these species is the size of the tepals, much smaller in 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D4728A36FBAEFE9B" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[885,1067,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D4728A36FBAEFE9B" box="[885,1067,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<quantity id="93429B2DFFF3FFE1D33F8A37FB38FE9A" box="[1080,1213,302,329]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="0.95" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.1 mm</quantity>
long, with prominent veins (
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D7D48A4AFF77FEBF" box="[211,242,339,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">vs.</emphasis>
2.5–3.0 mm long, with inconspicuous venation in 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D42D8A4AFC0CFEBF" authorityName="Opiz, Seznam Rostlin Kveteny Ceske" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Huds." box="[810,905,339,364]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D42D8A4AFC0CFEBF" box="[810,905,339,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (see 
<tableCitation id="19380373FFF3FFE1D4CA8A4BFB9BFEBF" box="[973,1054,338,364]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,224,592,616]" captionText="TABLE 1. Morphological comparison between Persicaria humboldtiana and P. minor." pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="540536C8FFF3FFE1D7BA8A6FFE9CFDF3" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,545]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
Other species similar to 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D6DD8A6EFD72FE43" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[474,759,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D6DD8A6EFD72FE43" box="[474,759,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D42A8A6EFF68FE67" authority="(Michaux 1803 a: 239) Small (1903: 378 - 379" authorityName="Small" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Michaux" baseAuthorityPageNumber="239" baseAuthorityYear="1803" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hydropiperoides">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D42A8A6EFB84FE43" box="[813,1025,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. hydropiperoides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF3FFE1D3148A6FFA80FE43" author="Michaux, A." box="[1043,1285,374,400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 29" refId="ref5625" refString="Michaux, A. (1803 a) Flora Boreali-Americana, vol. 1. C. Crapelet, Paris and Strassburg, 330 pp., plates 1 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 330" type="book chapter" year="1803">Michaux 1803a: 239</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF3FFE1D2108A6FFF68FE67" author="Small, J. K." pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref6169" refString="Small, J. K. (1903) Flora of the Southeastern United States. Published by the author, New York, 1370 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 133" type="book" year="1903">Small (1903: 378–379</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 1330), 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D64A8A82FD2CFE66" authority="Gray (1821: 269)" authorityName="Gray" authorityPageNumber="269" authorityYear="1821" box="[333,681,410,437]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maculosa">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D64A8A82FE53FE67" box="[333,470,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. maculosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF3FFE1D6E68A83FD2CFE66" author="Gray, S. F." box="[481,681,410,437]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref4678" refString="Gray, S. F. (1821) A Natural Arrangement of British Plants, vol. 2. Baldwin, Gradock, and Joy, London, 757 pp." type="book" year="1821">Gray (1821: 269)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D5E28A82FCD2FE67" box="[741,855,411,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setacea">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D5E28A82FCD2FE67" box="[741,855,411,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. setacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Baldwin 
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D4D48A82FC6CFE67" box="[979,1001,411,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF3FFE1D4F48A83FB4FFE66" author="Elliott, S." box="[1011,1226,410,437]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref4326" refString="Elliott, S. (1817) Sketch of the Botany of South-Carolina and Georgia, part 1 (5). J. R. Schenck, Charleston, 606 pp., 6 plates. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 9508" type="book" year="1817">Elliott [1817: 455]</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation id="302B4B39FFF3FFE1D3DB8A83FA22FE67" author="Small, J. K." box="[1244,1447,410,436]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref6169" refString="Small, J. K. (1903) Flora of the Southeastern United States. Published by the author, New York, 1370 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 133" type="book" year="1903">Small (1903: 379</bibRefCitation>
, 1330), but the size of the tepals are conspicuously bigger than in 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D46C8AA6FBA6FE0B" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[875,1059,446,472]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D46C8AA6FBA6FE0B" box="[875,1059,446,472]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; all these species has flowers with tepals longer than 
<quantity id="93429B2DFFF3FFE1D6518AFBFE2EFE2E" box="[342,427,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
long and sessile leaves, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="93BA4D4BFFF3FFE1D4278AFAFC52FE2F" authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[800,983,482,508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis id="66CEEADAFFF3FFE1D4278AFAFC52FE2F" box="[800,983,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tepals are 
<quantity id="93429B2DFFF3FFE1D3488AFBFB53FE2E" box="[1103,1238,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="0.95" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.1 mm</quantity>
long and its leaves are petiolate.
